ury area, functioning for well over a century as an all important link between the communities on either side of the River and as an essential component in a through route of importance in the development of the Sydney region. The series of major alterations to the structure since its construction articulate the continuing difficulties of negotiating a crossing of this major waterway with its frequent floods, however the bridge and its original piers have withstood the test of time. The Windsor Bridge has landmark qualities as one of only two bridge crossings of the Hawkesbury River in the Hawkesbury area and as such it defines the surrounding network of roads. It is a large structure, and although simple in appearance, impressive. The bridge represents a major engineering project in the State for its time. The iron caissons were cast at Mort's Dock in Balmain, using iron from the first short-lived iron mine in Australia (Fitzroy Mine).  They are lined with specially engineered and made bricks, then filled with concrete. The base of the main piers are the same ones sunk into the bedrock below the riverbed using pneumatic caissons in 1874.\n\nThe addition of a reinforced concrete beam deck to replace the timber deck in the 1920s is a relatively early use of this technology. The River and this crossing of it has defined the life of several generations of local inhabitants on both sides of the River. As the suburban outskirts of Sydney widen and come closer to the still distinct and distinctive Macquarie towns, the rich history of the area and its physical remains become increasingly important to the community's sense of identity. The Windsor Bridge is thus an important part of Windsor's history and identity.|Statement of significance, Heritage and conservation register, [[Roads & Maritime Services]], 21 October 2004.}}\n\n==Bridge replacement==\nIn December 2013, the [[Government of New South Wales]] gave planning approval to the construction of a new bridge to replace the existing 1874 Windsor Bridge that, due to safety reasons,<ref name=windsorbridge>{{cite web|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/sydney_region/western_sydney/windsor_bridge/index.html|title=Windsor Bridge replacement- Road Projects|publisher=Roads and Maritime Services|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> have been disputed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/sydney-traffic/windsor-bridge-plan-a-political-folly-say-engineers-20130102-2c5j2.html|title=Windsor Bridge plan a political folly, say engineers|author=Saulwick, Jacob|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=3 January 2013|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref> The old bridge is to be demolished after the new bridge opens. [[Roads & Maritime Services]] proposed to construct the new bridge {{convert|35|m}} downstream from the existing bridge. The approach road to the new bridge is proposed to be built along one side of the Thompson Square, Australia's oldest public square on a currently existing road. The new bridge proposal is objected to by in excess of 45,000 people, on the grounds that it will keep and increase heavy traffic in a historic town centre, destroys the town\u2019s character and heritage. Some who favour the proposal claim the new bridge would greatly reduce traffic congestion in the area, in direct contradiction to quite a number of government traffic studies and documents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-04/nsw-premier27s-office-accused-of-political-interference-in-win/5133396|title=NSW Premier's office accused of political interference in Windsor Bridge approval|author=Foschia, Liz|accessdate=15 January 2015|date=4 December 2013|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|location=Australia}}</ref> In October 2015, a legal challenge to stop the new bridge failed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/roads-and-maritime-services-pursues-windsor-bridge-community-group-in-court-20151029-gkmiew.html |title=Roads and Maritime Services pursues Windsor Bridge community group in court |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=2 November 2015 |access-date= |author= }}</ref><!-- A [[Legislative Council of New South Wales|NSW Legislative Council]] inquiry found the project was \"very close to malfeasance\".{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} A search of the Committee's report located [https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/lcdocs/inquiries/2468/Report%20-%20Windsor%20Bridge%20replacement%20project%20-%2022%20August%202018.pdf here] could find no reference to the word \"malfeasance\".-->\n\nThe replacement three-lane bridge is expected to provide insignificant improvements in traffic flow and flood mitigation. Some local residents believe that an agenda behind the bridge replacement is sand extraction on the Richmond Lowlands facilitated by the new bridge with wider spaced pylons and a slight height increases to allow barges to pass underneath. In a submission to a [[Legislative Council of New South Wales|NSW Legislative Council]] inquiry, it was opined that the new bridge was pushed forward largely by [[Bart Bassett]], the former [[Electoral district of Hawkesbury|Member for Hawkesbury]] and a former Mayor of the [[City of Hawkesbury]].<ref>{{cite web |author=name suppressed |url=https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/lcdocs/submissions/59433/0061%20Name%20suppressed.pdf |title=Submission No. 61 |work=INQUIRY INTO WINDSOR BRIDGE REPLACEMENT PROJECT: [[Legislative Council of New South Wales|NSW Legislative Council]] |publisher=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=11 January 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020 |page=2 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|New South Wales|Australian Roads}}}}\n*[[List of bridges in Sydney]]\n*[[Historic bridges of New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|author=Kass, Terry|title=RTA Thematic History: A component of the RTA Heritage and Conservation Register|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/environment/thematic-history-rta2006.pdf|type=PDF|work=[[Roads & Maritime Services|NSW Roads & Maritime Services]]|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]]|date=February 2006|edition=2nd |accessdate=12 January 2015}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/projects/sydney-west/windsor-bridge-replacement/index.html |title=Windsor Bridge replacement project website |work=[[Roads & Maritime Services]] |date= |publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]] }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/lcdocs/inquiries/2468/Report%20-%20Windsor%20Bridge%20replacement%20project%20-%2022%20August%202018.pdf |title=Windsor Bridge replacement project (Report no. 48) |author=Brown, Robert (Committee Chair) |location=Sydney, NSW |work=[[Legislative Council of New South Wales|NSW Legislative Council]], Portfolio Committee No. 5 \u2013 Industry and Transport |publisher=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=22 August 2018 |pages=xiii, 130 |isbn=978-19-2225-8564 }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/lcdocs/inquiries/2468/Windsor%20Bridge%20Inquiry%20-%20NSW%20Government%20Response.pdf |title=NSW Government response: Inquiry into the Windsor Bridge replacement project |author=Transport for New South Wales |author-link=Transport for New South Wales |location=Sydney, NSW |work= |publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]] |date=20 December 2018 |pages= |isbn= }}\n\n{{Bridges in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Road infrastructure in Sydney}}\n{{The Hawkesbury River|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Beam bridges]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1874]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Hawkesbury River]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:1874 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Windsor, New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBridge replacement:there is so much speculation and conjecture here", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windsor_Bridge_(New_South_Wales)"}
